SIMPLE: phenix
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Phenix
<hw>Phe"nix</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Phenixes</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>phoenix</ets>, Gr.
<grk>foi^nix</grk>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>ph⟦oe⟧nix</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Gr. Myth.)</fld> <def>A
bird fabled to exist single, to be consumed by fire by its own act, and
to rise again from its ashes. Hence, an emblem of immortality.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>A southern
constellation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A marvelous person or thing.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Latimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A person or thing that suffered destruction or
defeat and was restored to its former state.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>to rise like a phoenix</b></col>, <cd>to resume an
endeavor after an apparently final defeat.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Phenocryst</ent>⟦br⟧
